<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06062006 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06062006 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  The United States and 39 other countries signed a treaty in Montreal on Fridayto help forestall terrorism in the skies by making it easier to detect plasticexplosives at airports throughout the world. The agreement will requiremanufacturers in participating countries to add a chemical compound to plasticexplosives that will set off warning signals on commercially available vapordetectors. All the major manufacturing countries, including Czechoslovakia,the Soviet Union, Britain, France and Germany, signed the pact.Representatives of 35 other nations, including Cuba and Iran, signed aseparate document signaling later formal approval. Among those not representedat the conference were Iraq, Yemen and Libya.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  40 NATIONS SIGN PACT TO REDUCE TERROR INSKY  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Washington News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910302  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  9E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  111  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday March 2, 199100062006,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>